Power By Sample Sizes

power4test_by_n.Rd

Estimate power for a range of sample sizes.

The function get_rejection_rates_by_n() is used to extract the rejection rates form a get_rejection_rates_by_n object, with sample sizes added to the output.

Usage

power4test_by_n(object, n = NULL, progress = TRUE, ...)

get_rejection_rates_by_n(object_by_n)

Arguments

object

A power4test object.

n

A numeric vector of sample sizes for which the simulation will be conducted.

progress

Logical. Whether progress of the simulation will be displayed.

...

Arguments to be passed to power4test().

object_by_n

A power4test_by_n object, which is an output of power4test_by_n().

Value

The function power4test_by_n() returns a power4test_by_n object, which is a list of power4test objects, one for each sample size.

The function get_rejection_rates_by_n() returns a data frame which is similar to the output of get_rejection_rates(), with a column n added for the sample size for each test.

Details

This function regenerates datasets for a set of sample sizes and does the stored tests in each of them.

Optionally, it can also be run on a object with no stored tests. In this case, additional arguments must be set to instruct power4test() on the tests to be conducted.

It is usually used to examine the power over a range of sample sizes.

See also

power4test()

Examples



model_simple_med <-
"
m ~ x
y ~ m + x
"

model_simple_med_es <- c("y ~ m" = "l",
                         "m ~ x" = "m",
                         "y ~ x" = "n")

sim_only <- power4test(nrep = 2,
                       model = model_simple_med,
                       pop_es = model_simple_med_es,
                       n = 100,
                       R = 40,
                       ci_type = "boot",
                       fit_model_args = list(fit_function = "lm"),
                       do_the_test = FALSE,
                       iseed = 1234)
